{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_jasmine_ver01/data/sn78000533/00340580357/1949052601/0456.xml":{"full_text":"3\n\u2022t\nPAGE SIX\n.r\nv\nI 4\nLa\n3BR30S\nA. F. L. Executive Council Sets Wage\nPolitical And International Policies\nCleveland (LPA)\u2014The A FL ex\necutive council last week worked\nits way thru one of the heaviest\nagendas it has had before it in re\ncent years.\nAmong the major questions\nwhich the AFL\u2019s general staff dealt\nwith were:\n1. The effect of current econ\nomic developments upon this year\u2019s\ncontract negotiations.\n2. LLPE\u2019s nation-wide political\neducation program and the first\n'steps in the AFL\u2019s campaign to rid\n^Congress of Taft-Hartleyites.\ni 3. The current fight for Taft\nxHartley repeal.\n4. A FL policy in the internation\nal trade union meeting in Switzer\nland next month to set up a new\nworld labor organization.\nAfter hearing several reports on\nthe economic situation, the execu\ntive council adopted a resolution\ndeclaring that in its opinion the\nnation is not threatened with a de\npression \u201cas long as the purchas\ning power of American workers\nand the public as a whole remains\nhigh.\u201d\nBehind this green-light for four\nth-round wage demands is the\n'AFL\u2019s belief that the signs point\nto \u201ca continued period of high pro\nduction, substantial employment\nand prosperity.\u201d\nThe executive council\u2019s statement\ntook issue with pundits who have\nsighted a depression \u201cbecause the\npost-war era of automatic profits\nhas ended and industry is being\ncompelled to earn profits in a com\npetitive market.\u201d\nIt is only proper, the A FL\nspokesmen commented, that prices\nshould fall as production catches\nup with demand.\nThe executive council then com\nmented upon the use that labor\u2019s\nenemies are making of depression\ntalk to defeat progressive legisla\ntion.\n\u201cAnother group of reactionaries\nis using recession propaganda as\nan argument to curtail government\nspending, including many vitally\nneeded programs in the field of\nhousing, education and health.\nEven if their assumption were true\nand a recession on the way, that\nwould be all the more reason for\nthe government to continue spend\ning for constructive and\nprojects in order to take\nindustrial slack.\u201d\nworthy\nup any\nKeenan\npolitical\nLLPE Director Joseph\nreported on the AFL\u2019s\narm\u2019s plans for a thoro-going poli\ntical education program. Already\n100 radio stations are carrying\nYou Can See the Cream\nALWAYS USE\nCREAM TOP\nMilk Bottles\nTHEY ARE SANITARY\nUsed Exclusively By\nGolden Star\nDairy\nPhone 3200\n4\"------------------------------------------------\nLLPE\u2019s weekly discussion pro\ngrams, he said. LLPE has received\ncontributions of $500,000 from A FL\nunions to date, Keenan revealed.\nCommenting on Congressional\nfailure to repeal Taft-Hartley,\nKeenan declared that a switch in\nvoting by 20 Republicans or south\nern Democrats would do the trick.\nA resolution released by LLPE\u2019s\nadministrative committee declared\nthat its goal is the election of lib\nerals to Congress\u2014regardless of\nparty.\n\u201cEven a cursory analysis of the\nsituation in Congress reveals that\ninstead of a two-party system we\nhave a tug-of-war between, react\nionary forces in both parties on\none side and liberals from both\nparties on the other,\u201d the resolu\ntion pointed out.\nLabor has gotten \u201cscarcely any\ngreater comfort\u201d from the Demo\ncratic 81st Congress than it did\nfrom the Republican 80th, the\ncouncil said, \u201cWhat organized labor\nand the country needs is a large\nmajority of liberals in Congress,\nregardless of party affiliation.\u201d\nPresident Green told reporters\nthat the AFL is not disappointed\nwith Harry Truman\u2019s conduct in\nthe White House.\nKeenan said that a Congress\nman\u2019s vote on issues like Taft\nHartley repeal, housing, minimum\nwages and social security will de\ntermine the AFL\u2019s attitude towards\nhim in the 1950 elections.\nBy a unanimous vote the coun\ncil okayed AFL participation in the\nforthcoming international confer\nence to set up a new world-wide\norganization of free trade unions.\nPrevious AFL objections to a joint\ninternational with the CIO were\ndroppid.\nPresident Green reported that\nthe CIO has smoothed the way for\nthe joint effort by discarding its\nobjections to the AFL\u2019s status as\nsole representative of American\nlabor in the Int\u2019l Labor Organiza\ntion of the United Nations.\nThe executive council also reiter\nated the AFL\u2019s support of the\nNorth Atlantic Pact, and warned\nAmerican delegates on their way\nto the meeting of the \u201cBig Four\u201d\nforeign ministers in Paris to work\nfor a democratic Germany, and\nnot appease the Russians.\nFRIEND OF LABOR HONORED\nNew York (LPA)\u2014Prof. Will\niam Haber of the University of\nMichigan was chosen from a list of\nmore than 100 distinguished Am\nericans to receive the first annual\naward for human rehabilitation of\nthe American Organization for Re\nhabilitation Through Training Fed\neration. 1LGWU President David\nDubinsky made the presentation.\nAs a liberal economist and long\ntime friend of labor, Prof. Haber\nhas championed liberal labor leg\nislation for many years and is an\nexpert in the field of labor-man\nagement relations.\nThe best fun we get out of a\nvacation is thinking about it in\nadvance.\nSomerset Hotel\nSPECIAL PRICES TO POTTERS\nAmerican Plan COC *er Week\nRooms With Meals Two In Room\nNEWLY RENOVATED THROUGHOUT\n133-35-37 S. Arkansas Ave.\u2014Atlantic City\nTWO BLOCKS FROM CONVENTION HALL\nPotters Will Receive Same Meals As In Former Years\nFuneral\nCosts\nDawson\nACTUAL charges for 500 consecu\ntive funerals conducted by the\nDAWSON\nfollowsl\n\u201cSO MUCH ioc\nFuneral Home are as\nWere\nWere\nWere\nWere\n50%\nUnder $150\nUnder $300\nUnder $500\nOver $500\nFuneral Home\nk\nHttl*\"\n215 Wwt nth StrMt Phon* Main 10\nTHE BOYS IN THE BACK ROOM LOSE OUT\u2014Franklin\nRoosevelt Jr. smiles as he pulls the lever to vote for himself in the New\nYork 20th district Congressional election to replace the late Rep. Sol\nBloom. Roosevelt was still smiling at the end of the day. He had beaten\nthe Tammany machine by an overwhelming lead. It was the second\ntime within two weeks that a labor-backed candidate triumphed over\nan established political machine. The first marked the defeat of Boss\nFrank Hague in Jersey City.\nI\nUnions Replacing Machine\nAs Key To City Politics\nThe history of organized labor in\nnorthern big city politics is an in\nteresting and seldom understood\none. Over a hundred years ago in\nfant unions along the east coast\nhad their political action leagues\nwhich fought\u2014often successfully\u2014\nto break the hold that the merchant\naristocracy then had on state and\ncity government.\nDuring the latter half of the\n19th century a tremendous number\nof people\u2014many from Europe, but\na big number too from the less\nprosperous parts of rural America\n\u2014poured into the cities. Most of\nthem weren\u2019t ready for unionism.\nSuch little protection as they re\nceived from the hazards of indus\ntrial life came from the vote-get\nting machines usually Demo\ncratic.\nOrganized labor was a rather\nsmall minority in the metropolitan\nareas. The principal opposition to\nthe Democratic machines was the\nRepublican party. Usually it too\nran a machine operation, occasion\nally posing as the champion of good\ngovernment against corruption of\nthe more successful machines.\nOften independent liberals and all\nor part of the trade union move\nment joined with the Republicans\nin purging city administrations,\ntemporarily.\nBut the Republican\u2014good gov\nernment-labor coalitions couldn\u2019t\nhold together. Not only were, the\nRepublican organizations unwilling\nto meet labor\u2019s social demands on\nthe cities, but their Congressional\nrepresentatives consistently oppos\ned labor\u2019s national legislative pro\ngrams.\nSo, except for brief periods when\na particular Democratic machine\nbecame too crooked to stomach\nmost unions tended to work along\nwith it.\nthe picture has changed,\nmembers now constitute a\nfraction of the voters in\nbig cities. Direct benefits\nBut\nUnion\nmajor\nmost\nfrom union action, and social leg\nislation, not the handouts of the\nbosses, are the workers\u2019 protections\nagainst the hazards of an unstable\neconomy.\nUnions are demanding, and get\nting, more of a role in drafting\nparty programs and choosing can\ndidates. And now they are in a\nposition to demand that the welfare\nof the people, not the machine, be\nthe key to Democratic city politics.\nThat\u2019s what labor in New York\ndid when it told the Tammany\ncrowd it wouldn\u2019t go along with its\nattempt to perpetuate machine\nrule, and side-track the candidacy\nof FDR Jr., whom the unions think\nwill be an outstanding liberal Con\ngressman.\nWith its election of Roosevelt,\nNY labor has sounded the death\nknell of the racketeers\u2019 grip on the\nDemocratic party in Manhattan. It\nhas proven that the boys in the\nback room can\u2019t defy the organized\nworkers and get away with it\u2014\neven when they have the tacit sup\nport of Rep. Vito Marcantonio and\nhis pro-Communist American Labor\nParty.\nTHE POTTERS HERALD\nFord Charged With\nStalling On New\nContract Talks\nThe election of Franklin D.4^Z Z ZT\nRoosevelt Jr. to Congress from a\nManhattan district last week, un\nderlines an important change in\nthe basic structure of American\npolitics. Support of the trade union\nmovement, not the nod of an old\nline political machine, is the great\nest asset a candidate for public of\nfice can have.\nJust a week before young Roose\nvelt shellaced the Tammany nom\ninee in New York\u2019s 20th Congress\nional District, Jersey City union\nvoters made the same point when\nthey overturned the 32 year rule\nof Boss Hague.\nDetroit (LPA) United Auto\nWorkers President has announced\nthat he will file unfair labor prac\ntice charges against the Ford\nMotor Co. for \u201cdelaying contract\nnegotiations.\u201d\nThis is the third week of a strike\nof 65,000 UAW members against\nspeedup of assembly lines at the\nFord Rouge plant. The auto union\nchi\u2018f claims that the company is\nusing the strike as a \u201csubterfuge\nto delay contract talks\u201d on the\nUAW-Ford agreement covering\n106,000 production workers thru\nout the country, which expires\nearly in July. Bargaining on the\nimportant contract was to have\nstarted no later than May 15.\nThe UAW set the May date for.\nnegotiations on pensions, wage in\ncreases and other such demands\nlong before the speedup strike be\ncame necessary, Ford now charges\nthat the demand for contract talks\nis \u201can attempt to broaden the is\nsues of the strike.\u201d The company\nrefuses to start discussing con\ntract terms before June 1\u2014and\nthen only if the present strike is\nsettled. Ford is the only auto man\nufacturer whose contract with\nUAW expires completely this year\nand it is there that the union plan\nned to set the pattern for the in\ndustry.\nOn insistence of the union, the\ncompany finally wired the Federal\nMediation Conciliation service\nlast week that it would back down\non its refusal to let government\nmediators sit in on .the strike talks.\nDirector Cyrus Ching had assign\ned FMCS regional director Arthur\nC. Viat to try to bring about agree\nment in the Rouge dispute but\nFord had told Viat they \u201cpreferred\nto be left alone.\u201d\nMore Political\nAction Theme Of\nLabor Convention\nno\nPullman Strike Cancelled\nChicago (LPA)\u2014There\u2019ll be\nstrike of sleeping car conductors\non the Pullman System. That was\nassured last week when the Order\nof Railway Conductors reached an\nagreement with the management\nsettling a big backlog of griev\nances. Earlier, the Conductors had\nordered a stoppage if no satisfac\ntory settlement were secured. The\nstrike order has now been cancel\nled.\nJefferson City (LPA)\u2014Intensi\nfied political action in support of\nlabor\u2019s objective was the theme of\nthe Missouri Federation of Labor's\nconvention last week.\nFirst struck by President Reuben\nT. Wood, the theme carried over\ninto virtually every speech made,\nu nd every resolution passed by 600\ndt\u2018legates.\nNumber one target of Missouri\nlabor\u2019s political offensive in 1950\nwill be reactionary Sen. Forrest\nDonnell (R) who, in the delegates\u2019\nopinion, has been a spokesman in\nCongress for special interests, not\nthe people of Missouri. Also mark\ned for defeat was Rep. Dewey\nShort (R) long famous as one of\nthe most primitive minds in Con\ngress.\nOne convention speaker, Secre\ntary Joseph P. Clarke of the Fire\nmen Oilers Int\u2019l Union-AFL,\nformer president of the St. Louis\nTrades Labor Council, empha\nsized that labor must be as alert in\ncombating big business lobbyists\nin Washington and in the state\ncapitals between elections as it is\nin fighting them on election day. I\nClarke declared that successful\npolitical action depends upon unit-]\n\u00bb*d efforts by A FL, CIO and unaffil\niated unions. I\nRepeal of the Madison and King\nThompson- laws\u2014Missouri\u2019s little\nTaft-Hartley\u2014was listed as\nstate federation\u2019s immediate\njective.\nthe\nob-\nop\nits\nIn addition to reiterating its\nposition to Taft-Hartley and\nsupport of improvements in feder\nal minimum wage legislation, the\nconvention also enthusiastically en\ndorsed President Truman\u2019s nation\nal health program.\nDemand the Union Label.\nr*-. .1 v y-\nEAST LIVERPOOL, OHIO\nNew Rent Boosts\nRending In Fla.,\nNebraska Towns\nWashington (LPA)\u2014Three more\nstates were closer to a general de\ncontrol of all rents this week, and\nthe nation\u2019s second largest city will\nbe the locale of hearings on pro\nposals for a general rent rise.\nIn Nebraska, the state legisla\nture has approved a measure allow\ning the governor to lift all rent\ncontrols between npw and Nov. 1.\nThe Texas House has approved a\ngeneral lifting of rent controls, but\nthe Senate has not yet acted. In\nFlorida, the House has also ap\nproved decontrol, but the Senate\nhas not yet acted, and Gov. Fuller\nWarren says he\u2019ll veto the mea\nsure.\nD.\nChicago tenants will be heard,\nalong with landlords advocating a\ngeneral rent boost, before the Area\nRent Advisory Board in hearings\nthe first week in June. The board\nhas already conducted a survey of\nthe rental housing situation. Chic\nago landlords are Strongly organ\nized, and were the major- users of\nthe 15% \u201cvoluntary\u201d rent boost\nprovision of the old rent control\nlaw.\nUnder provision of the 1949 law,\nHousing Expediter Tighe Woods\nlast week lifted rent controls in\nHialeah, Fla., where the city coun\ncil has voted decontrol, and at\nArlington Farms near Washington,\n\u201cgovernment girls\u201d housing pro\nject, on the grounds that a. 6\nvacancy rate existed. Management\nof Arlington Farms had threaten\ned to close up altogether unless\nthey got a rent boost.\nst\nBERNARD R. REYNOLDS\nBernard R. Reynolds, 945 Mor\nton St., died May 19 in City Hospi\ntal following a long illness of sili\ncosis. He was 66.\nMr. Reynolds was bom in New\nport and lived in East Liverpool\nsince a child. He resided with a\nsister, Mrs. Lottie Murphy. He was\na caster and was employed last by\nthe Hall China Co. He was a mem\nber of Local Union No. 4, National\nBrotherhood of Operative Potters\nand the First Baptist Church.\nHe leaves a son, Fred Reynolds,\nand two daughters in Buffalo, N.\nY. \u2018two brothers, Oscar A. Rey\nnoldiof East Liverpool, and Del-,\nvan C. Reynolds of Salem a sis\nter, Mrs. Howard Mackey, also of\nEast Liverpool, ami 11 grand\nchildren.\nMRS. JOSEPH I. DICKEY\nMrs. Violet M. Dickey, 39, wife\nof Joseph I. Dickey, 914 St. Clair\nAve., died May 19, in the Presby\nterian Hospital, Pittsburgh, fol\nlowing a long illness.\nMrS. Dickey was born in Indus\ntry *Mnd lived in Canonsburg, Pa.,\nfor 13 years before she came to\nEast Liverpool 12 years ago. She\nwas employed in the decorating\nshop at Plant 8 of the Homer\nLaughlin China Co. She was a\nnumber of Local Union 124, Na\ntional Brotherhood of Operative\nPotters.\nSift leaves her parents, Mr. and\nMrs. Albert Prideau of Canons\nburg three sisters, Mrs. Albert\nHatala and Mrs. Samuel Kanotz\nof Canonsburg, and Mrs. Carl Fritz\nof Washington, Pa., and a brother,\nHarry Prideau of East Liverpool.\nRites were held in the Hinton\nand Griffith Funeral Home in Can\nonsburg by Rev. F. S. Eberle,\npastor of St. Paul\u2019s Lutheran\nChurch there. Burial was in Can\nonsburg.\nWILLIAM MITCHELL\nTrenton, N. J.\u2014William Mitchell,\nan employee of the Scammell China\nCo. for the past 55 years, died\nMarch 25, following a lengthy ill\nness.\nMr. Mitchell took an active part\nin Brotherhood affairs and was a\ncharter member of Local Union 91\nuntil it amalgamated in later years\nwith Local Union 35.\nSurvivors include his wife, Mrs.\nMyrtle Mitchell, one daughter,\nMrs. Marie Thorn and one grand\ndaughter.\nBuy Union-Made goods from\nothers aa you would have them\npay Union wages unto you!,\nPAULETTE GODDARD\u2014If you\nwant to see more of this girl her\ncurrent strip is \u201cBride of Venge\nance\u201d co-starring John Lund.\nDenham Ain\u2019t\nBoss NLRB\nFinally Rules\nlong\nWashington (LPA)\u2014In a\nawaited decision, the NLRB last\nweek said that it is the boss\u2014not\nGeneral Counsel Robert N. Den\nham. The five board members were\nunanimous in their ruling.\nThe Taft-Hartley law gives the\ngeneral counsel full authority to\nissue or refuse to issue unfair\nlabor practice complaints against\nunions and employers. In keeping\nwith T-H logic, the law requires\nhim to move against unions in cer\ntain types of cases. But a large\narea of discretion was left to Den\nham in the handling of cases\nbrought by both workers and em\nployers.\nDenham' has construed this to\nmean that the board must accept\nevery case, no matter how remote\nfrom interstate commerce, that he\ndecides he wants to play around\nwith. In one of the two cases de\ncided this week he had maintained\nthat his authority \u201cprecludes the\nboard from refusing to assert jur\nisdiction.\u201d\nBut, replied the board, altho\nDenham has the power to start an\naction against a union or an em\nployer it has a right to decide,\nwhen the case has worked its way\nthru T-H procedures to the NLRB\nproper, whether to take jurisdic\ntion or not.\n\u201cHe is to investigate and pro\nsecute, but the board is to judge,\u201d\nsaid the five officials, in the most\nstinging rebuke Denham has re\nceived to date.\nDenham\u2019s contention, they point\ned out, argues \u201cagainst the very\ntheory of separation of functions\nwhich gave rise to Congressional\nestablishment of the independent\noffice of general counsel.\n\u201cSeparation of functions was\nevidently intended to bar judges\nfrom being prosecutors surely\nCongress was not seeking, by the\nsame provision to convert prose\ncutors into judges,\u201d the board re\nmarked. \u201cIt is clear that the Gen\neral Counsel alone was to exercise\ndiscretion as to the issuance of\ncomplaints, but it is equally clear\nthat his judgement was not to con\ntrol the board at the decisional\nstage of any proceeding.\u201d\nOver Denham\u2019s strenuous opposi\ntion the board refused to take jur\nisdiction in two small cases that he\nwas pushing\u2014one brought against\nan employer by an AFL federal\nlocal, and one brought against the\nRetail Clerks Int\u2019l Association\nAFL by a photographers\u2019 supply\nstore.\nBreakfast Cheer coffee served\nfree at Potters Picnic.\nRESOLUTIONS OF RESPECT\nWhereas, Almighty God in His infinite wisdom, has seen\nto take from our midst our friend and fellow worker,\nw\nfit ____________ __________________\nBrother Joseph Kennedy, respected and admired for his fel\nlowship and character, and\nWhereas, We the members of Local Union 86, recognize\nthe loss of this Brother, shall cherish and respect the mem\nory of his pleasant manner and as evidence of sympathy and\nesteem, it fs hereby further,\nResolved, That we extend our profound sympathy to\nhis family, a copy of this resolution be published in our\n'\u2019Official journal, The Potters Herald, a copy spread upon the\nminutes of the Local and a copy sent to the bereaved family.\nthe bereaved family,\ndraped in mourning for a period of\nAlso that our charter be draped in mourning for a period of\nthirty days.\nROLAND C. EDGAR,\nGEORGE MULLEN\nFRANK WEBBER.\nLabor will consider its responsi\nbilities from international, nation\nal, and state viewpoints, hearings\naddresses by outstanding labor and\npublic affairs speakers. In order\nthat this year\u2019s sessions will be\nboth educational and practical,\nsmall group discussions and work\nshops on educational techniques\nwill be introduced for the first\ntime.\nAmong the outstanding subjects\nin the 4-day program are: Guiding\nOurselves Toward Democracy, Can\nWe Achieve World Recovery, Us\ning Atomic Energy Constructively,\nDeveloping A Sound Tax Program,\nLabor Legislation In The 81st Con\ngress, A National Health Insur\nance Plan, New Jersey Attacks The\nHousing Problem, and Labor In\nThe Community.\nThe program for this year\u2019s in\nstitute is being planned by a joint\ncommittee of 56 representatives of\nRutgers University, State Federa\ntion of Labor, and Workers Educa\ntion Bureau of America, co-spon\nsors of the annual project. Vincent\nJ. Murphy, mayor of Newark and\nsecretary of the New Jersey State\nFederation of Labor, and Prof.\nIrvine Kerrison, in charge of the\nlabor program of the Rutgers In\nstitute of Management and Labor\nRelations, are chairman and secre\ntary respectively of the joint com\nmittee.3 r.\u201d\nCANT BLAME LABOR\nWashington (LPA) The old\nargument that labor\u2019s to blame \u00abfor\nthe high cost of house construction\nisn\u2019t true. According to an article\nappearing in the May issue of the\nLabor Department\u2019s Monthly Labor\nReview, pay roll at the site ac\ncounted for about 1/3 of total\nhouse construction costs in 1946-47,\nthe same proportion as for 1931-32.\nYOUR!\nIN COLOR BY v\nTECHNICOLOR^\nMICHAEL CURTIZ\nPRODUCTION\nDORIS W\nJACKfflMN\nLEE BOWMAN\nBUMHSMLCuDoces\u2019S.Z.EVEADOLPHE\nSELENA ROYLE\nDIRECTED BY\nMICHAEL CURTIZ\nThursday, May 26, 1949\nLabor\u2019s Responsibility For Building\nDemocratic World Is Institute Theme\nNew Brunswick, N. J. (ILNS).\u2014\nLabor\u2019s responsibility in building a\ndemocratic world will be examined\nby members of the New Jersey\nState Federation of Labor at their\n19th Annual Rutgers Labor Insti\ntute convening on the New Bruns\nwick campus of the State Univer\nsity June 13 through 16.\nNo Discrimination Rule Upheld\nRichmond, Va. (LPA)\u2014Another\nstep in the fight to give Negroes\nthe franchise in the South was\ntaken recently. The US Fourth Cir\ncuit Court of Appeals upheld, a\nDistrict Court decree enjoining\nSouth Carolina\u2019s Democratic party\nfrom denying Negroes full parti\ncipation in the party because of\ncolor. Circuit Court Judge John J.\nParker stated that barring Negroes\nfrom Democratic clubs, which con\ntrol southern primaries, is indir\nectly but nevertheless plainly un\nconstitutional.\nINSURED\nFirst Federal Savings\nLoan Association\n1032 Pennsylvania Ave.\nCERAMIC\n5 DAYS COMMENCING SUNDAY\n9\ni\u2019\nt.\nscreen Play by Harry\nMime tar Hany Warren urica W Ralph\nHERE\u2019S\n^JHE\nBIGTIME\nSPRINGTIME\nLOVE-TIME\nMUSICAL\nSMASH\nFROM\nWARNER\nBROS!\nU\nKurnitz and Dane Lussier\nMusical Diraction Ray Heindori\nHmw\nSHORT FEATURES\nMISSISSIPPI HARE\nSWIM PARADE\nNEWS of the DAY in PICTURES\njjF","height":"26475","width":"21315"}}
